{"title_page": "Bill Dunn (American politician)", "text_new": "<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Bill Dunn headshot.jpg|thumb|right|Rep. Bill Dunn]] -->\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Bill Dunn\n|office       = Speaker pro tempore of the [[Tennessee House of Representatives]]\n|term_start   = January 8, 2019\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Curtis Johnson (politician)|Curtis Johnson]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[List of Speakers of the Tennessee House of Representatives|Speaker of the Tennessee House of Representatives]]<br>Acting\n|term_start1  = August 2, 2019\n|term_end1    = August 23, 2019\n|predecessor1 = [[Glen Casada]]\n|successor1   = [[Cameron Sexton]]\n|state_house2 = Tennessee\n|district2    = 16th\n|term_start2  = January 20, 1994\n|term_end2    = \n|predecessor2 = Charles Severance\n|successor2   = \n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1961|7|3}}\n|birth_place  = [[Panama Canal Zone]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Stacy Dunn\n|children     = 5\n|education    = [[University of Tennessee|University of Tennessee, Knoxville]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]], [[Master of Science|MS]])\n}}\n'''William \"Bill' K. Dunn''' is an [[United States|American]] politician, a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], and the former Acting-Speaker of the [[Tennessee House of Representatives]]. Rep. Dunn announced on September 12, 2019 that he would not seek re-election to his post.<ref>https://www.knoxnews.com/story/news/politics/2019/09/12/knoxvilles-bill-dunn-announces-he-wont-run-re-election/2300123001/</ref>\n\nBill Dunn was born July 3, 1961 in the [[Panama Canal Zone]] to Paul and Mary Dunn.  Bill Dunn and his wife Stacy have five children and are members of Holy Ghost Catholic Church of [[Knoxville, Tennessee]].<ref>http://www.billdunn.org/About_Bill.php About Bill.</ref>{{Self-published source|date=February 2017}}\n\n==Biography==\nDunn first earned a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[animal science]] during 1983 and later completed a [[Master of Science]] degree in Extension Education from the [[University of Tennessee]] during 1985. Dunn worked as a federal employee for the U.S. Agricultural Extension Service as a [[4-H]] agent in [[Grainger County]], Tennessee, for approximately eight years. Dunn reportedly received several awards for his work in 4-H youth development.<ref>http://www.billdunn.org/About_Bill.php About Bill.</ref>{{Self-published source|date=February 2017}} Dunn is a certified [[arborist]] and General Manager of Cortese Tree Specialists of Knoxville.<ref>http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/24395/bill-dunn#.U-zhluNdXhc Bill Dunn's Biography.</ref> Dunn is now{{When|date=July 2015}} employed by QualPro.\n\n==Tennessee House of Representatives==\n\nBill Dunn has served as a state representative following his moving back to Knox County as to buy his parents' home during 1993 and later being elected to the 99th [[Tennessee General Assembly]] during 1994. Dunn represents the 16th district of the Fountain City, Halls Crossroads, and Powell areas of [[Knoxville]], part of [[Knox County, Tennessee|Knox County]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/19970601225951/http://www.legislature.state.tn.us/house/members/h16.htm \"Tennessee House Member\".] Legislative Information Services. Accessed December 30, 2006.</ref>\n\nPrior to December 2006, Bill Dunn served as the House Republican Leader.<ref>[http://www.nashvillecitypaper.com/index.cfm?section=9&screen=news&news_id=53663 \"GOP lawmakers buck leadership, pick new ones\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070103222515/http://www.nashvillecitypaper.com/index.cfm?section=9&screen=news&news_id=53663 |date=January 3, 2007 }} ''Nashville City Paper''. Accessed December 30, 2006.</ref> Afterward, he was appointed by his successor as Republican Leader to be the freshman coordinator for the House Republican Caucus.<ref>[http://www.chattanoogan.com/articles/article_98496.asp \"Dunn Appointed Freshman Coordinator For Tennessee House Republican Caucus\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022111111/http://www.chattanoogan.com/articles/article_98496.asp |date=October 22, 2007 }} Chattanoogan.com. December 18, 2006.</ref> Currently, Bill Dunn is the Vice Chair of the House Public Transportation and Highways Subcommittee. He is a member of the House Agriculture Committee, the House Finance Ways and Means Committee, the House Government Operations Committee, the House Calendar and Rules Committee, the House Public Transportation and Highways Subcommittee, and the House Environment Subcommittee.<sup>1</sup>\n\nDunn authored and was the prime Tennessee House sponsor of marriage amendment against legal [[gay marriage]] and also House co-sponsor of the proposed abortion amendment to the Tennessee State Constitution, more commonly referred as Senate Joint Resolution 127, or simply, SJR 127 (the enactment SJR 127 will appear on the November, 2014 Tennessee general election ballot as amendment question 1). Enactment of the Senate Joint Resolution 127 in various form has been a \"primary objective\" of Tennessee Right to Life since 2001 and versions of SJR 127 have already passed the Tennessee state Senate four times prior to 2008.<ref>http://www.lifenews.com/2008/05/01/state-3188/ \"Tennessee Pro-Life Legislators Fail to Revive Amendment to Limit Abortions\".</ref>\n\nDunn will become the Acting Speaker when Speaker [[Glen Casada]]'s resignation takes effect on August 2, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|last=Whetstone|first=Tyler|date=May 21, 2019|title=Knoxville's Bill Dunn: Willing to serve as Speaker, would bring 'boredom' to House|url=https://knoxnews.com/amp/3751894002|work=Knoxville News-Sentinel|location=Knoxville, Tennessee|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref>\n\n==Tennessee Right to Life, Inc.==\n\nDunn's wife, Stacy Dunn, currently receives annual compensation of $23,400 as a vice president of Tennessee Right to Life, Inc.<ref>http://www2.guidestar.org/FinDocuments/2012/621/009/2012-621009171-09da1505-9O.pdf 2012 IRS Form 990, Tennessee Right to Life, Inc. p.7</ref> and his father Paul Dunn was a former president<ref>http://www.christiangallery.com/UTSabotage.htm ''Tennessee Right To Life, Inc. Attempts To Sabotage Horsley Speaking Engagement At the University of Tennessee''.</ref> and manager of the Knoxville affiliate chapter of Tennessee Right to Life, Inc. Paul Dunn once allegedly extended an offer for the \"Knoxville Right to Life\" (''sic''; Knox County affiliate of Tennessee Right to Life) to pick up the hotel bill for [[Neal Horsley]] to speak on a March 13, 2003 event then sponsored by the University of Tennessee Pro-Life Collegians at the University Center auditorium on the University of Tennessee campus in Knoxville.<ref>http://www.christiangallery.com/UTSabotage.htm ''Tennessee Right To Life, Inc. Attempts To Sabotage Horsley Speaking Engagement At the University of Tennessee''.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.billdunn.org Official site]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-tn-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Curtis Johnson (politician)|Curtis Johnson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Speaker pro tempore of the [[Tennessee House of Representatives]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Glen Casada]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Speakers of the Tennessee House of Representatives|Speaker of the Tennessee House of Representatives]]<br>Acting|years=2019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Cameron Sexton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current Speakers of U.S. state Houses of Representatives}}\n{{Tennessee House of Representatives |state= collapsed}}\n{{Current Tennessee statewide political officials}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dunn, Bill}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Tennessee House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Knoxville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Republicans]]\n[[Category:University of Tennessee alumni]]\n[[Category:Zonians]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Bill Dunn headshot.jpg|thumb|right|Rep. Bill Dunn]] -->\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Bill Dunn\n|office       = Speaker pro tempore of the [[Tennessee House of Representatives]]\n|term_start   = January 8, 2019\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Curtis Johnson (politician)|Curtis Johnson]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[List of Speakers of the Tennessee House of Representatives|Speaker of the Tennessee House of Representatives]]<br>Acting\n|term_start1  = August 2, 2019\n|term_end1    = August 23, 2019\n|predecessor1 = [[Glen Casada]]\n|successor1   = [[Cameron Sexton]]\n|state_house2 = Tennessee\n|district2    = 16th\n|term_start2  = January 20, 1994\n|term_end2    = \n|predecessor2 = Charles Severance\n|successor2   = \n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1961|7|3}}\n|birth_place  = [[Panama Canal Zone]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Stacy Dunn\n|children     = 5\n|education    = [[University of Tennessee|University of Tennessee, Knoxville]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]], [[Master of Science|MS]])\n}}\n'''William \"Bill' K. Dunn''' is an [[United States|American]] politician, a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], and the former Acting-Speaker of the [[Tennessee House of Representatives]]. Rep. Dunn announced on September 12, 2019 that he would not seek re-election to his post.<ref>https://www.knoxnews.com/story/news/politics/2019/09/12/knoxvilles-bill-dunn-announces-he-wont-run-re-election/2300123001/</ref>\n\nBill Dunn was born July 3, 1961 in the [[Panama Canal Zone]] to Paul and Mary Dunn.  Bill Dunn and his wife Stacy have five children and are members of Holy Ghost Catholic Church of [[Knoxville, Tennessee]].<ref>http://www.billdunn.org/About_Bill.php About Bill.</ref>{{Self-published source|date=February 2017}}\n\n==Biography==\nDunn first earned a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[animal science]] during 1983 and later completed a [[Master of Science]] degree in Extension Education from the [[University of Tennessee]] during 1985. Dunn worked as a federal employee for the U.S. Agricultural Extension Service as a [[4-H]] agent in [[Grainger County]], Tennessee, for approximately eight years. Dunn reportedly received several awards for his work in 4-H youth development.<ref>http://www.billdunn.org/About_Bill.php About Bill.</ref>{{Self-published source|date=February 2017}} Dunn is a certified [[arborist]] and General Manager of Cortese Tree Specialists of Knoxville.<ref>http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/24395/bill-dunn#.U-zhluNdXhc Bill Dunn's Biography.</ref> Dunn is now{{When|date=July 2015}} employed by QualPro.\n\n==Tennessee House of Representatives==\n\nBill Dunn has served as a state representative following his moving back to Knox County as to buy his parents' home during 1993 and later being elected to the 99th [[Tennessee General Assembly]] during 1994. Dunn represents the 16th district of the Fountain City area of [[Knoxville]], which is currently part of [[Knox County, Tennessee|Knox County]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/19970601225951/http://www.legislature.state.tn.us/house/members/h16.htm \"Tennessee House Member\".] Legislative Information Services. Accessed December 30, 2006.</ref>\n\nPrior to December 2006, Bill Dunn served as the House Republican Leader.<ref>[http://www.nashvillecitypaper.com/index.cfm?section=9&screen=news&news_id=53663 \"GOP lawmakers buck leadership, pick new ones\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070103222515/http://www.nashvillecitypaper.com/index.cfm?section=9&screen=news&news_id=53663 |date=January 3, 2007 }} ''Nashville City Paper''. Accessed December 30, 2006.</ref> Afterward, he was appointed by his successor as Republican Leader to be the freshman coordinator for the House Republican Caucus.<ref>[http://www.chattanoogan.com/articles/article_98496.asp \"Dunn Appointed Freshman Coordinator For Tennessee House Republican Caucus\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022111111/http://www.chattanoogan.com/articles/article_98496.asp |date=October 22, 2007 }} Chattanoogan.com. December 18, 2006.</ref> Currently, Bill Dunn is the Vice Chair of the House Public Transportation and Highways Subcommittee. He is a member of the House Agriculture Committee, the House Finance Ways and Means Committee, the House Government Operations Committee, the House Calendar and Rules Committee, the House Public Transportation and Highways Subcommittee, and the House Environment Subcommittee.<sup>1</sup>\n\nDunn authored and was the prime Tennessee House sponsor of marriage amendment against legal [[gay marriage]] and also House co-sponsor of the proposed abortion amendment to the Tennessee State Constitution, more commonly referred as Senate Joint Resolution 127, or simply, SJR 127 (the enactment SJR 127 will appear on the November, 2014 Tennessee general election ballot as amendment question 1). Enactment of the Senate Joint Resolution 127 in various form has been a \"primary objective\" of Tennessee Right to Life since 2001 and versions of SJR 127 have already passed the Tennessee state Senate four times prior to 2008.<ref>http://www.lifenews.com/2008/05/01/state-3188/ \"Tennessee Pro-Life Legislators Fail to Revive Amendment to Limit Abortions\".</ref>\n\nDunn will become the Acting Speaker when Speaker [[Glen Casada]]'s resignation takes effect on August 2, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|last=Whetstone|first=Tyler|date=May 21, 2019|title=Knoxville's Bill Dunn: Willing to serve as Speaker, would bring 'boredom' to House|url=https://knoxnews.com/amp/3751894002|work=Knoxville News-Sentinel|location=Knoxville, Tennessee|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref>\n\n==Tennessee Right to Life, Inc.==\n\nDunn's wife, Stacy Dunn, currently receives annual compensation of $23,400 as a vice president of Tennessee Right to Life, Inc.<ref>http://www2.guidestar.org/FinDocuments/2012/621/009/2012-621009171-09da1505-9O.pdf 2012 IRS Form 990, Tennessee Right to Life, Inc. p.7</ref> and his father Paul Dunn was a former president<ref>http://www.christiangallery.com/UTSabotage.htm ''Tennessee Right To Life, Inc. Attempts To Sabotage Horsley Speaking Engagement At the University of Tennessee''.</ref> and manager of the Knoxville affiliate chapter of Tennessee Right to Life, Inc. Paul Dunn once allegedly extended an offer for the \"Knoxville Right to Life\" (''sic''; Knox County affiliate of Tennessee Right to Life) to pick up the hotel bill for [[Neal Horsley]] to speak on a March 13, 2003 event then sponsored by the University of Tennessee Pro-Life Collegians at the University Center auditorium on the University of Tennessee campus in Knoxville.<ref>http://www.christiangallery.com/UTSabotage.htm ''Tennessee Right To Life, Inc. Attempts To Sabotage Horsley Speaking Engagement At the University of Tennessee''.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.billdunn.org Official site]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-tn-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Curtis Johnson (politician)|Curtis Johnson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Speaker pro tempore of the [[Tennessee House of Representatives]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Glen Casada]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Speakers of the Tennessee House of Representatives|Speaker of the Tennessee House of Representatives]]<br>Acting|years=2019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Cameron Sexton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current Speakers of U.S. state Houses of Representatives}}\n{{Tennessee House of Representatives |state= collapsed}}\n{{Current Tennessee statewide political officials}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dunn, Bill}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[